<doc id="61190" wikidata="Q834025" url="?curid=61190" title="Cauchy's integral theorem">
<text>In mathematics, the Cauchy integral theorem (also known as the Cauchy–Goursat theorem) in complex analysis, named after Augustin-Louis Cauchy (and Édouard Goursat), is an important statement about line integrals for holomorphic functions in the complex plane. Essentially, it says that if formula_1 is holomorphic in a simply connected domain Ω, then for any simply closed contour formula_2 in Ω, that contour integral is zero. 

formula_3

==Statement==
=== Fundamental theorem for complex line integrals ===
If is a holomorphic function on an open region , and formula_4 is a curve in from formula_5 to formula_6 then,
formula_7

Also, when has a single-valued antiderivative in an open region , then the path integral formula_8 is path independent for all paths in .

==== Formulation on simply connected regions ====

Let formula_9 be a simply connected open set, and let formula_10 be a holomorphic function. Let formula_11 be a smooth closed curve. Then:
formula_12
(The condition that formula_13 be simply connected means that formula_13 has no &quot;holes&quot;, or in other words, that the fundamental group of formula_13 is trivial.)

==== General formulation ====

Let formula_9 be an open set, and let formula_10 be a holomorphic function. Let formula_11 be a smooth closed curve. If formula_4 is homotopic to a constant curve, then:
formula_12
(Recall that a curve is homotopic to a constant curve if there exists a smooth homotopy (within formula_13) from the curve to the constant curve. Intuitively, this means that one can shrink the curve into a point without exiting the space.) The first version is a special case of this because on a simply connected set, every closed curve is homotopic to a constant curve.

==== Main example ====

In both cases, it is important to remember that the curve formula_4 does not surround any &quot;holes&quot; in the domain, or else the theorem does not apply. A famous example is the following curve: 
formula_23
which traces out the unit circle. Here the following integral:
formula_24
is nonzero. The Cauchy integral theorem does not apply here since formula_25 is not defined at formula_26. Intuitively, formula_4 surrounds a &quot;hole&quot; in the domain of formula_28, so formula_4 cannot be shrunk to a point without exiting the space. Thus, the theorem does not apply.

==Discussion==
As Édouard Goursat showed, Cauchy&#x27;s integral theorem can be proven assuming only that the complex derivative formula_30 exists everywhere in formula_13. This is significant because one can then prove Cauchy&#x27;s integral formula for these functions, and from that deduce these functions are infinitely differentiable.

The condition that formula_13 be simply connected means that formula_13 has no &quot;holes&quot; or, in homotopy terms, that the fundamental group of formula_13 is trivial; for instance, every open disk formula_35, for formula_36, qualifies. The condition is crucial; consider
formula_37
which traces out the unit circle, and then the path integral
formula_38
is nonzero; the Cauchy integral theorem does not apply here since formula_25 is not defined (and is certainly not holomorphic) at formula_26.

One important consequence of the theorem is that path integrals of holomorphic functions on simply connected domains can be computed in a manner familiar from the fundamental theorem of calculus: let formula_13 be a simply connected open subset of formula_42, let formula_10 be a holomorphic function, and let formula_4 be a piecewise continuously differentiable path in formula_13 with start point formula_46 and end point formula_47. If formula_48 is a complex antiderivative of formula_28, then
formula_50

The Cauchy integral theorem is valid with a weaker hypothesis than given above, e.g. given formula_13&quot;,&quot; a simply connected open subset of formula_42, we can weaken the assumptions to formula_28 being holomorphic on formula_13 and continuous on formula_55 and formula_4 a rectifiable simple loop in formula_55.

The Cauchy integral theorem leads to Cauchy&#x27;s integral formula and the residue theorem.

==Proof==
If one assumes that the partial derivatives of a holomorphic function are continuous, the Cauchy integral theorem can be proven as a direct consequence of Green&#x27;s theorem and the fact that the real and imaginary parts of formula_58 must satisfy the Cauchy–Riemann equations in the region bounded by and moreover in the open neighborhood of this region. Cauchy provided this proof, but it was later proven by Goursat without requiring techniques from vector calculus, or the continuity of partial derivatives.

We can break the integrand as well as the differential formula_59 into their real and imaginary components:

formula_60
formula_61

In this case we have
formula_62

By Green&#x27;s theorem, we may then replace the integrals around the closed contour formula_4 with an area integral throughout the domain formula_64 that is enclosed by formula_4 as follows:

formula_66
formula_67

But as the real and imaginary parts of a function holomorphic in the domain formula_68 and formula_69 must satisfy the Cauchy–Riemann equations there:
formula_70
formula_71

We therefore find that both integrands (and hence their integrals) are zero

formula_72
formula_73

This gives the desired result
formula_74

