<doc id="61213" wikidata="Q425432" url="?curid=61213" title="Laurent series">
<text>In mathematics, the Laurent series of a complex function formula_1 is a representation of that function as a power series which includes terms of negative degree. It may be used to express complex functions in cases where a Taylor series expansion cannot be applied. The Laurent series was named after and first published by Pierre Alphonse Laurent in 1843. Karl Weierstrass had previously described it in a paper written in 1841 but not published until 1894.

==Definition==
The Laurent series for a complex function formula_1 about an arbitrary point formula_3 is given by
formula_4
where the coefficients formula_5 are defined by a contour integral that generalizes Cauchy&#x27;s integral formula:
formula_6

The path of integration formula_7 is counterclockwise around a Jordan curve enclosing formula_3 and lying in an annulus formula_9 in which formula_1 is holomorphic (analytic). The expansion for formula_1 will then be valid anywhere inside the annulus. The annulus is shown in red in the figure on the right, along with an example of a suitable path of integration labeled formula_7. When formula_7 is defined as the circle formula_14, where formula_15, this amounts
to computing the complex Fourier coefficients of the restriction of formula_16 to formula_7. The fact that these integrals are unchanged by a deformation of the contour formula_7 is an immediate consequence of Green&#x27;s theorem. 

One may also obtain the Laurent series for a complex function formula_1 at formula_20. However, this is the same as when formula_21. 

In practice, the above integral formula may not offer the most practical method for computing the coefficients
formula_5 for a given function formula_1; instead, one often pieces together the Laurent series by combining known Taylor expansions. Because the Laurent expansion of a function is unique whenever
it exists, any expression of this form that equals the given function 
formula_1 in some annulus must actually be the Laurent expansion of formula_1.

== Convergence ==

Laurent series with complex coefficients are an important tool in complex analysis, especially to investigate the behavior of functions near singularities.

Consider for instance the function formula_26 with formula_27. As a real function, it is infinitely differentiable everywhere; as a complex function however it is not differentiable at formula_28. The Laurent series of formula_29 is obtained via the power series representation,
formula_30
which converges to formula_29 for all formula_32 except at the singularity formula_28. The graph on the right shows formula_29 in black and its Laurent approximations
formula_35
As formula_36, the approximation becomes exact for all (complex) numbers formula_37 except at the singularity formula_38.

More generally, Laurent series can be used to express holomorphic functions defined on an annulus, much as power series are used to express holomorphic functions defined on a disc.

Suppose 
formula_39
is a given Laurent series with complex coefficients formula_5 and a complex center formula_3. Then there exists a unique inner radius formula_42 and outer radius formula_43 such that:
* The Laurent series converges on the open annulus formula_44. That is, both the positive- and negative degree power series converge. Furthermore, this convergence will be uniform on compact sets. Finally, the convergent series defines a holomorphic function formula_1 on formula_9.
* Outside the annulus, the Laurent series diverges. That is, at each point in the exterior of formula_9, either the positive- or negative degree power series diverges.
* On the boundary of the annulus, one cannot make a general statement, except that there is at least one point on the inner boundary and one point on the outer boundary such that formula_1 cannot be holomorphically extended to those points; giving rise to a Riemann-Hilbert problem.

It is possible that formula_42 may be zero or formula_43 may be infinite; at the other extreme, it&#x27;s not necessarily true that formula_42 is less than formula_43.
These radii can be computed by taking the limit superior of the coefficients formula_5 such that:
formula_54

When formula_55, the coefficient formula_56 of the Laurent expansion is called the residue of formula_1 at the singularity formula_3. For example, the function
formula_59
is holomorphic everywhere except at formula_60. The Laurent expansion about formula_61 can then be obtained from the power series representation:
formula_62
hence, the residue is given by formula_63.

Conversely, for a holomorphic function formula_1 defined on the annulus formula_44, there always exists a unique Laurent series with center formula_3 which converges (at least on formula_9) to formula_1.

For example, consider the following rational function, along with its partial fraction expansion:
formula_69

This function has singularities at formula_70 and formula_71, where the denominator is zero and the expression is therefore undefined.
A Taylor series about formula_60 (which yields a power series) will only converge in a disc of radius 1, since it &quot;hits&quot; the singularity at formula_70.

However, there are three possible Laurent expansions about 0, depending on the radius of formula_74:

* One series is defined on the inner disc where ; it is the same as the Taylor series, formula_75 This follows from the partial fraction form of the function, along with the formula for the sum of a geometric series, formula_76 for formula_77.
* The second series is defined on the middle annulus where formula_78 is caught between the two singularities: formula_79 Here, we use the alternative form of the geometric series summation, formula_80 for formula_81.
* The third series is defined on the infinite outer annulus where formula_82, (which is also the Laurent expansion at formula_83) formula_84 This series can be derived using geometric series as before, or by performing polynomial long division of 1 by formula_85, not stopping with a remainder but continuing into formula_86 terms; indeed, the &quot;outer&quot; Laurent series of a rational function is analogous to the decimal form of a fraction. (The &quot;inner&quot; Taylor series expansion can be obtained similarly, just by reversing the term order in the division algorithm.)

== Uniqueness ==
Suppose a function formula_1 holomorphic on the annulus formula_88 has two Laurent series:
formula_89

Multiply both sides by formula_90, where k is an arbitrary integer, and integrate on a path γ inside the annulus,
formula_91

The series converges uniformly on formula_92, where &quot;ε&quot; is a positive number small enough for &quot;γ&quot; to be contained in the constricted closed annulus, so the integration and summation can be interchanged. Substituting the identity
formula_93
into the summation yields
formula_94

Hence the Laurent series is unique.

== Laurent polynomials ==
A Laurent polynomial is a Laurent series in which only finitely many coefficients are non-zero. Laurent polynomials differ from ordinary polynomials in that they may have terms of negative degree.

== Principal part ==

The principal part of a Laurent series is the series of terms with negative degree, that is
formula_95

If the principal part of formula_16 is a finite sum, then formula_16 has a pole at formula_3 of order equal to (negative) the degree of the highest term; on the other hand, if formula_16 has an essential singularity at formula_3, the principal part is an infinite sum (meaning it has infinitely many non-zero terms).

If the inner radius of convergence of the Laurent series for formula_16 is 0, then formula_16 has an essential singularity at formula_3 if and only if the principal part is an infinite sum, and has a pole otherwise.

If the inner radius of convergence is positive, formula_16 may have infinitely many negative terms but still be regular at formula_3, as in the example above, in which case it is represented by a &quot;different&quot; Laurent series in a disk about formula_3.

Laurent series with only finitely many negative terms are well-behaved—they are a power series divided by formula_107, and can be analyzed similarly—while Laurent series with infinitely many negative terms have complicated behavior on the inner circle of convergence.

== Multiplication and sum ==
Laurent series cannot in general be multiplied.
Algebraically, the expression for the terms of the product may involve infinite sums which need not converge (one cannot take the convolution of integer sequences).
Geometrically, the two Laurent series may have non-overlapping annuli of convergence.

Two Laurent series with only &quot;finitely&quot; many negative terms can be multiplied: algebraically, the sums are all finite; geometrically, these have poles at formula_3, and inner radius of convergence 0, so they both converge on an overlapping annulus.

Thus when defining formal Laurent series, one requires Laurent series with only finitely many negative terms.

Similarly, the sum of two convergent Laurent series need not converge, though it is always defined formally, but the sum of two bounded below Laurent series (or any Laurent series on a punctured disk) has a non-empty annulus of convergence.

Also, for a field formula_109, by the sum and multiplication defined above, formal Laurent series would form a field formula_110 which is also the field of fractions of the ring formula_111 of formal power series.

== See also ==
* Puiseux series
* Mittag-Leffler&#x27;s theorem
* Formal Laurent series Laurent series considered &quot;formally&quot;, with coefficients from an arbitrary commutative ring, without regard for convergence, and with only &quot;finitely&quot; many negative terms, so that multiplication is always defined.
* Z-transform the special case where the Laurent series is taken about zero has much use in time-series analysis.
* Fourier series the substitution formula_112 transforms a Laurent series into a Fourier series, or conversely. This is used in the &quot;q&quot;-series expansion of the &quot;j&quot;-invariant.
* Padé approximant Another technique used when a Taylor series is not viable.

